                <h2>Weekly Observation: Creative Assets Hitting a Wall During Cold Start</h2>
<p>This week, several TikTok Shop accounts managed by Yiyu Digital Media showed similar symptoms:</p>
<ul>
<li>CTR looked decent in the first 3 days, but CPM started climbing rapidly by day 4</li>
<li>The same set of creatives performed with over 40% variance across different ad sets</li>
<li>The team produced 20 video assets, yet fewer than 5 achieved stable conversions</li>
</ul>
<p>The root cause isn't account authority — it's <strong>insufficient creative pool depth</strong>. During the cold start phase, TikTok's algorithm needs enough creative signals to learn about your target audience. When creative types are too homogeneous, the system quickly exhausts the creative space and falls into efficiency decay.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Root Causes: Three Common Cold Start Mistakes</h2>
<h3>Mistake 1: Copy the Winner</h3>
<p>One utility app team saw a competitor's product review video go viral and directly replicated the script and scene with 10 variations. In practice, CTR was only 60% of the original while CPM ran 30% higher. The reason is straightforward: TikTok's deduplication mechanism actively suppresses similar content, and user tolerance for repetitive scenes drops within 48 hours.</p>
<h3>Mistake 2: Volume Is Enough</h3>
<p>The common saying during cold start is "start with 20 creatives." But if all 20 are vertical talking-head videos with product close-ups, the algorithm receives homogeneous signals, making the effective exploration space equivalent to a single creative. <strong>Diversity</strong> and <strong>quantity</strong> matter equally.</p>
<h3>Mistake 3: Optimize After Scaling</h3>
<p>Some teams operate with a "spend first, optimize later" mindset, not stratifying creatives during cold start and mixing them freely. This approach might have worked during TikTok Shop's growth phase, but with current CPM levels, it causes cold start costs to exceed projections by 1.5–2x.</p>
<hr />
<h2>4-Step SOP for Building Your Creative Pool</h2>
<h3>Step 1: Define 3 Anchor Creatives</h3>
<p>Before launching ads, preset 3 anchor creatives corresponding to different conversion paths:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Anchor A (Pain Point)</strong>: Hook viewers in the first 3 seconds with a usage scenario pain point, e.g., "I've been using this wrong for three years"</li>
<li><strong>Anchor B (Result)</strong>: Open with before/after comparisons or high-light moments of influencer usage</li>
<li><strong>Anchor C (Trust)</strong>: Compile real user reviews or show factory/warehouse footage to emphasize supply chain reliability</li>
</ul>
<p>These 3 anchors don't aim for viral hits — they provide the algorithm with baseline conversion signals.</p>
<h3>Step 2: Build a 5×3 Matrix Around Each Anchor</h3>
<p>Each anchor generates 5 variations, totaling 15 creatives:</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Variation Dimension</th>
<th>Example</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Duration</td>
<td>15s, 30s, 60s versions</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Music</td>
<td>Original audio, trending BGM, instrumental</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Captions</td>
<td>No subtitles, animated captions, highlighted text</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><strong>Key Principle</strong>: Change only one variable at a time. Never alter multiple dimensions simultaneously, or you won't be able to identify which factor drove the performance difference.</p>
<h3>Step 3: Stratified Creative Delivery</h3>
<p>Allocate the 15 creatives across different ad sets by quality tier:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Test Layer ($20–$30/day)</strong>: Distribute all 15 creatives evenly to quickly identify assets with CTR &gt; 1% and CPC &lt; $0.5</li>
<li><strong>Scale Layer</strong>: Move creatives with positive ROAS into dedicated ad sets, gradually increasing budget to 40% of daily spend</li>
<li><strong>Elimination Layer</strong>: Pause creatives with CTR &lt; 0.5% and no conversions after $50 spend</li>
</ul>
<h3>Step 4: 72-Hour Review and Creative Refresh</h3>
<p>Conduct a creative pool update meeting every 72 hours during cold start, focusing on:</p>
<ul>
<li>Which anchor (A/B/C) delivers the most consistent CTR</li>
<li>Whether new variations need to be added (e.g., usage scenarios mentioned in comments)</li>
<li>Whether eliminated creatives can be revived through re-editing</li>
</ul>
<hr />
<h2>This Week's Recommendations: Prioritize These Two Actions Next Week</h2>
<ol>
<li>
<p><strong>Embed actionable hooks in anchor creatives</strong>: Data from multiple categories this week shows that creatives with urgency cues like "this price is only available today" achieved Add to Cart Rates 22% above average. During cold start, don't worry about pressuring users — the algorithm cares more about immediate action intent.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Build a creative recovery mechanism</strong>: One cross-border e-commerce team we spoke with this week quickly replenished their creative pool by cutting 3–5 highlight clips from livestream replays. They found that short clips edited from replays within 24 hours of going live felt more natural than scripted videos, with average viewer watch time 15 seconds longer.</p>
</li>
</ol>
<hr />
<p>Cold start isn't about "spending money waiting for a viral hit." It's about <strong>using sufficiently diverse creative signals to help the algorithm quickly find people willing to buy.</strong> The depth of your creative pool determines the efficiency ceiling of your cold start period.</p>
